observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Adhere strictly with Section 2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 as well as the procurement rules and procedures of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and strengthen the internal control system on procurements;

Stop the practice of paying supplier/ dealer/payee through cash from the concerned officers/personnel which are intended to be reimbursed later.   Instead, strictly follow the imprest system which requires that all payments be made by check.

We recommended that Management direct the officers concerned to:
Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards (SLC), Subsidiary Ledgers (SL), and Stock Cards for the inventory accounts;
Consolidate weekly the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) for the issued supplies and materials to be used as basis for recording issued and ending inventory amounts;
Properly use the chart of accounts as stated in Annex B of Circular No. 2015-009.
We likewise recommended that Management create an Inventory Committee that will conduct semestral physical count of inventories and report the complete details in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI); and designate permanent personnel who will be in charge of monitoring the receipt and issuance/utilization of supplies and materials.

We recommended that Management:
Stop the granting of additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled;
prepare and issue demand letters to concerned officers and employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances.
Locate those concerned officers and employees with long outstanding unliquidated cash advances, especially the non-LGU officers and deceased officers/employees, and issue them or their heirs demand letters requiring immediate settlement or liquidation of cash advances;
Institute appropriate legal actions/sanctions for non-settlement and non-liquidation of cash advances in accordance to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-004 and other existing laws and regulations, if warranted; and
Ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances is in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the officers/personnel involved in the procurement process to plan their activities including the probable goods and services that will be utilized and incorporate them in the Annual Procurement Plan;

Adhere strictly with Section 2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 as well as the procurement rules and procedures of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and strengthen the internal control system on procurements;

Make use of petty cash fund to cover purchases involving small amounts for ordinary and essential needs of the Municipality; and

Stop the practice of paying supplier/ dealer/payee through cash from the concerned officers/personnel which are intended to be reimbursed later.   Instead, strictly follow the imprest system which requires that all payments be made by check.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Review the amount of transfers to Trust Liability-DRRM account in the Trust Fund books, and effect the necessary correcting journal entries in the books if there are errors found;

Prepare the MDRRMF Utilization Report using the prescribed format in Annex B of COA Circular 2012-002, and submit the same to the Audit Team;

Maintain Subsidiary Ledger for each source of DRRM Funds and for each year of transfer of unexpended balances to the special trust fund; and

Provide disclosure in Notes to the Financial Statements regarding amount and details of the unexpended balance of MDRRMF as of year-end, using the format prescribed under Annex D of the aforementioned COA Circular.

We likewise recommended that Management utilize the alternative modes of procurement prescribed under Sections 48 to 53 of the IRR of RA 9184, if warranted, ensuring that checks for payments will be drawn only once the goods/services were already delivered/rendered and the procurement process is completely undertaken.

